not possible, by application before the Tribunal. Once this period or any extension has expired, the Act is clear that the Commission\'92s authority to prosecute lapses.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 25. Thus the Act, if not expressly, at the very least by implication, contemplates two distinct periods in the gestation of a complaint before the Commission. First, an investigation period in which the Commission decides whether to refer the complaint or 
not, or with the consent of the respondent to enter into a consent agreement contemplated in section 49D; second, a litigation period if the Commission decides to refer the matter to the Tribunal, which is the period {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i \'93after the completion of the investigat
ion\'94} that runs from the date of the filing of the referral until the conclusion of the proceedings. As long as the Commission files its complaint referral, which is the pleading that initiates the litigation period, within the prescribed period, it retains
 the title to prosecute the matter, and does not lose this title, irrespective of the time it takes to conclude the matter. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 26. It is possible that the Commission and a respondent may not be able to agree on the terms of a consent order during the investigation period, but do so during the litigation period. It is for this reason that section 49D(1), contemplating this, refers 
