he consent order. If the consent order does not find favour with the Tribunal the Commission retains its title to prosecute. Section 49D(2) makes it clear that apart from approving a consent order the Tribunal is entitled to either indicate changes it want
s before it will make such an order or refuse to grant such an order.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s10\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs20\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0\ltrch\hich\lang1033\loch\lang1033 Section 49D(2) provides as follows:}
