\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs20\lang2057\f6\fs20\f4\fs20\lang1025\qj (a)\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s10\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang2057\loch\f4\fs20\lang2057{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0{\ltrch\hich\lang1033\loch\lang1033 make the order as agreed to and proposed by the Competition Commission and the }}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\lang1033\i\loch\lang1033\i respondent}{\ltrch\hich\lang1033\loch\lang1033 ;}}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs20\lang1033\f6\fs20\f4\fs20\lang1025\qj (b)\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s10\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 indicate any changes that must be made in the draft order before it will make the order; or}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\fs20\lang1033\f6\fs20\f4\fs20\lang1025\qj (c)\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s10\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 refuse to make the order. }}}
{\*\cs20\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } If the Commission has lost its title to prosecute at this stage, then it is helpless to respond if the Tribunal wants changes to the order to which the respondent won\'92t agree, or if the
 Tribunal refuses to grant the consent order. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 29. It seems clear that the Commission must retain its title to prosecute at the time a consent order application has been launched to avoid it facing prosecutorial impotence if the Tribunal does not sanction its bargain with the respondent. It can retain 
this title to prosecute either (a) by having the consent application considered during the one year period or an extended period or (b) after this period, {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i provided} it has referred the complaint to the Tribunal during this period thus preserving that right.
 The legislature intended that once a matter had been non-referred by the Commission it washed its hands of the matter and had no further right or interest in the complaint including the right to settle it by way of a consent order. At this stage having no
n\'96referred, whether expressly or by way of inference, the Commission effectively vacates the battlefield with the respondent in favour of the complainant. It follows logically that this schema contemplates a period during which the Commission is unrestrict
ed by the complainant in dealing with the complaint and thereafter, if not otherwise disposed of by the Commission by way of referral or a consent order, the complainant, with its full rights restored, may prosecute the matter unrestricted by the Commissio
n.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s14\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 30. Thus, the power to prosecute and the power to settle are coextensive; once the former is lost so is the latter. This is not a case of having to read in language into section 49D(1). If one follows the procedural evolution of a complaint - how the Commi
ssion enjoys the monopoly power to prosecute and how it can lose this right to a complainant \'96 then one need not read in words to the section, one simply follows the schema and logic of the Act to appreciate that the legislature never contemplated conferri
ng the power to settle to exist independently of the power to prosecute. It is precisely for this reason that the Commission is given such a long period to investigate a complaint and to apply to extend it. It must during this period of investigation decid
e whether to refer or settle a complaint. If it refers it can of course settle it later. What it may not do is to investigate, decide not to refer or settle and then at some later time decide it should enter into a settlement agreement for a consent order.
 Nor should it, as happened in this case, enter into some contract (as opposed to a consent agreement contemplated in section 49D) with a respondent not to prosecute further, in return for some quid pro quo, unless it fully appreciates the legal implicatio
ns of doing this. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\cf1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 31. Nor does Tribunal rule 24, on which the applicant seeks to rely as a further plank for its argument, take the matter any further. At best it constitutes another re-expression of section 49D(1). It does not answer, expressly or by implication, the quest
ion of whether the Commission can settle when it has lost its power to prosecute. If anything rule 24(3) which states that the party filing the notice must serve it on the complainant and request the complainant to inform the Commission whether it is willi
ng to accept damages in the order, and if so amount claimed, suggests that this is all happening while the Commission\'92s prosecutorial power is alive, otherwise what would be the point of all this if the complainant had already received or been deemed to ha
ve received, a notice of non-referral and was in the process of initiating its own complaint.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 32. One can easily see what absurdities would result if the title to prosecute and settle were not coextensive. In the first place there is the fact that the Commission is left in a position of a contracting party not a prosecuting party in approaching set
tlement negotiations with the respondent, which cannot be in the public interest. The ability to approach a settlement negotiation with the threat of proceeding is vital to a proper bargaining process. A further concern is that the only time a consent orde
r would be likely, after the title to prosecute has lapsed, is when a respondent faces a complainant in a non-referral situation or a new complaint based on a previous complaint that was not prosecuted. The respondent, anxious to constrain the complainant\'92
s range of remedies, then enters into a consent order with the Commission, the effect of which is to limit the private complainant\'92s remedies to those contemplated in section 49D(4).{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s10\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs20\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 Note that under section 49D (4) the complainant is confined to two remedies - the voiding of an agreement, and a declaration that the conduct is unlawful. Any other remedy such as an interdict, or access, etc. would not be available to it, unless the cons
ent order provided for them. We do not need to decide whether the private complainant can press for the imposition of an administrative penalty as the AHF complainants were seeking. Even if this remedy is only available to the Commission to contend for, a 
consent agreement still bars the private complainant from a number of remedies that it might otherwise wish to seek to remedy its complaint. Note that in relation to the interdict remedy the courts have decided in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Ansac v Botash, [2005] 1 CPLR 18 (CAC)}{\cf2  }tha
t such a remedy is open to a private complainant.}}}
{\*\cs20\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } Now of course that presupposes that the Commission will allow itself to 
be used to those ends. However, the expedient motive of a respondent may not always be that transparent to the Commission, especially if it was not a complaint that it referred, and it may be persuaded that the complainant is unreasonably pursuing the resp
ondent and that a good settlement is available to the Commission even in this case it had not sought to prosecute. The legislature never contemplated placing the Commission in this sort of situation as a settler of last resort \'96 once it lost its title to p
rosecute the fate of the litigation is left to the private complainant and the respondent to resolve. Nor as a matter of public policy is it desirable that a body charged with policing legislation be left with a residual power to settle when its primary po
